00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:04.500
Welcome my friend to today's
lecture on negotiable instruments.

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:07.290
This concept looks scary, don't worry.

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:12.600
We've brought snacks and
metaphors, concept, explanation.

00:00:13.454 --> 00:00:17.415
So what are these negotiable instruments
everyone keeps talking about?

00:00:17.835 --> 00:00:23.564
Just think of them as very official
written IOUs that can be passed around.

00:00:24.045 --> 00:00:27.854
They are written documents that
promise to pay a specific amount of

00:00:27.854 --> 00:00:32.549
money to a specific person or even
to whoever is holding the document.

00:00:32.890 --> 00:00:37.990
The bearer, the best part is they
are super easily transferable from

00:00:37.990 --> 00:00:42.250
one person to another, either by
just handing it over, which is mere

00:00:42.250 --> 00:00:47.440
delivery, or by signing it over, which
is called endorsement and delivery.

00:00:47.890 --> 00:00:52.420
Now, the person who receives this
instrument in good faith, and for some

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:58.810
value, we call this hero a holder in due
course, gets a perfect clean title to it.

00:00:59.235 --> 00:01:04.245
This title is free from any story
or defects from previous holders.

00:01:04.665 --> 00:01:08.445
This feature makes them a
wonderfully convenient and secure

00:01:08.445 --> 00:01:12.825
way to move funds or credit around
without carrying bricks of cash.

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:17.520
As per the big rule book, the
Negotiable Instruments Act of

00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:20.340
1881, there are three main types.

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:22.289
First, the promissory note.

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:27.690
This is a simple written promise from
one person, the maker to another person.

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:32.100
The payee promising to pay a certain
sum of money, either right away

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:34.380
on demand or at a future date.

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:39.660
The maker must sign it and the promise
must be completely unconditional.

00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:41.115
No ifs or buts.

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.130
Next is the Bill of Exchange.

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:48.060
This one is a written
order here, one person.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:53.880
The draw is ordering another person, the
drawee, to pay a certain sum of money to a

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:56.610
third person, the payee or to the bearer.

00:01:57.030 --> 00:02:00.210
This can also be on demand
or at a future time.

00:02:00.539 --> 00:02:05.595
It must be signed by the draw, and very
importantly, accepted by the drawing.

00:02:06.495 --> 00:02:08.354
Finally we have the check.

00:02:08.535 --> 00:02:10.965
Ah, the one we all know and use.

00:02:11.325 --> 00:02:15.525
A check is just a special kind of
bill of exchange that is always

00:02:15.525 --> 00:02:19.515
drawn on a specified banker and
is always payable on demand.

00:02:19.935 --> 00:02:23.415
It is, without a doubt, the most
common negotiable instrument

00:02:23.505 --> 00:02:25.365
for our day-to-day transactions.

00:02:26.415 --> 00:02:27.855
Real world relevance.

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:31.530
Now you might be thinking,
why should I care?

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:36.810
Understanding negotiable instruments is
absolutely crucial because they are the

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:39.240
very backbone of banking operations.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:44.400
Making financial transactions happen
securely and efficiently every single day.

00:02:44.820 --> 00:02:49.500
If you want to work in a bank, proficiency
in this area is non-negotiable.

00:02:49.830 --> 00:02:53.790
It ensures you handle customer
funds accurately and follow all

00:02:53.790 --> 00:02:55.260
the legal banking standards.

00:02:55.870 --> 00:03:00.549
The key areas of relevance include
handling check operations, which is all

00:03:00.549 --> 00:03:03.160
about deposits, withdrawals and clearing.

00:03:03.609 --> 00:03:07.630
Promissory notes are very often
a key part of loan documentation.

00:03:08.019 --> 00:03:12.010
In the world of international business,
builds of exchange are vital for

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:14.260
trade finance to secure payments.

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:18.640
Good customer service means being
able to explain different payment

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:20.185
methods and their implications.

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:25.870
It's also critical for fraud prevention,
helping you spot any irregular or forged

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:30.970
instruments, and of course, for legal
compliance, making sure every transaction

