00:05:38.739 --> 00:05:40.030
Methods of solving.

00:05:40.664 --> 00:05:44.895
To solve problems related to negotiable
instruments, you need a systematic

00:05:44.895 --> 00:05:46.875
approach, almost like a detective.

00:05:47.174 --> 00:05:49.575
First, identify the instrument type.

00:05:49.844 --> 00:05:51.585
Is it a promise or an order?

00:05:51.885 --> 00:05:53.174
How many parties are there?

00:05:53.325 --> 00:05:54.674
Is it payable on demand?

00:05:55.065 --> 00:05:58.844
This tells you if it's a promissory
note, bill of exchange, or check.

00:05:59.205 --> 00:06:01.275
Second, identify the parties.

00:06:01.604 --> 00:06:06.284
You must be able to name the draw,
drawee, pay maker, and so on.

00:06:06.284 --> 00:06:09.945
In any scenario, this is the
key to understand who is liable.

00:06:10.364 --> 00:06:12.075
Third, determine validity.

00:06:12.435 --> 00:06:14.955
Check if the instrument
meets all legal rules.

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:16.110
Is it in writing?

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:20.190
Signed unconditional for a
certain sum with certain parties.

00:06:20.430 --> 00:06:24.360
Fourth, analyze the negotiation,
trace how the instrument was

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:28.500
transferred, noting each endorsement,
and whether the new holder is just

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:30.630
a holder or a holder in due course.

00:06:30.984 --> 00:06:33.294
Fifth, assess dishonor scenarios.

00:06:33.594 --> 00:06:37.375
If it's dishonored, find out
why and determine who is liable

00:06:37.494 --> 00:06:41.034
and what steps like sending a
notice of dishonor must be taken.

00:06:41.455 --> 00:06:45.804
Lastly, calculate maturity if
it applies for time instruments.

00:06:45.864 --> 00:06:50.094
Calculate the exact due date and don't
forget to add grace days if they are

00:06:50.094 --> 00:06:53.635
applicable Shortcuts and smart techniques.

00:06:54.210 --> 00:06:58.380
Here are some quick shortcuts
for spotting the instrument type.

00:06:58.469 --> 00:07:04.770
Look for keywords I promise to pay
screams promissory note, pay to X or

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:10.620
order points to a bill of exchange or a
check if it's drawn on a bank and payable

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:13.380
on demand for party identification.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:17.490
Remember the one making the promise
is the maker in a promissory note.

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:22.500
The one giving the order is the
draw of a bill of exchange or check.

00:07:22.950 --> 00:07:28.050
The one order to pay is the draw,
and the one who gets the money is

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:31.170
always the pay for the HDC rule.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:36.419
Just remember the magic words
value good faith before maturity.

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:37.919
No notice of defect.

00:07:38.415 --> 00:07:42.135
